00:13:56,195 --> 00:13:57,497
About what?

256
00:13:57,530 --> 00:13:59,198
You'll find out.

257
00:14:01,468 --> 00:14:05,004
[door clanging and shutting]

258
00:14:05,037 --> 00:14:06,805
This is Art Bradley.

259
00:14:06,839 --> 00:14:08,874
He's the head
prosecutor on your case,

260
00:14:08,907 --> 00:14:10,577
and this is Agent Tucker.

261
00:14:10,610 --> 00:14:12,911
He's with the FBI and is
in charge of the investigation.

262
00:14:12,945 --> 00:14:16,449
We ran background
checks on Mr. Otis here.

263
00:14:16,483 --> 00:14:19,818
It turns up, Amos Otis
served two tours in Iraq.

264
00:14:19,852 --> 00:14:22,254
Since being discharged,
he's held various jobs.

265
00:14:22,288 --> 00:14:24,056
The last one as a roofer.

266
00:14:34,333 --> 00:14:35,535
You know this man?

267
00:14:39,305 --> 00:14:40,406
No, I don't.

268
00:14:40,440 --> 00:14:42,141
Ever seen him before?

269
00:14:42,642 --> 00:14:44,109
I don't know him.

270
00:14:44,143 --> 00:14:46,045
That's enough. He answered you.

271
00:14:46,378 --> 00:14:49,882
This is the Amos Otis
your truck is registered to.

272
00:14:50,517 --> 00:14:51,451
He's black.

273
00:14:52,284 --> 00:14:56,088
He's not some
lily white guy and he's dead.

274
00:14:56,523 --> 00:14:58,257
Okay. I think we're done here.

275
00:14:58,290 --> 00:15:00,392
- Did you kill him?
- I said we're done.

276
00:15:00,427 --> 00:15:01,528
He was buried two weeks ago.

277
00:15:02,394 --> 00:15:05,331
We're getting permission
to exhume the body as we speak.

278
00:15:06,098 --> 00:15:09,001
What's going on here?
What's your name?

279
00:15:09,034 --> 00:15:11,203
I thought I was Amos Otis.

280
00:15:11,236 --> 00:15:12,371
Didn't you?

281
00:15:12,404 --> 00:15:13,939
That's not your fucking name.

282
00:15:14,206 --> 00:15:16,008
[Jason] That's it.
I need to talk with my client.

283
00:15:16,041 --> 00:15:17,276
You need to get out of here.

284
00:15:17,544 --> 00:15:19,378
You need to figure
out who your client is.

285
00:15:19,411 --> 00:15:21,246
No, that's your problem
and Agent Tucker's.

286
00:15:21,280 --> 00:15:22,582
Now get the fuck out of here.

287
00:15:23,082 --> 00:15:24,183
Right.

288
00:15:24,216 --> 00:15:26,051
[door buzzing and clanging]

289
00:15:26,085 --> 00:15:29,421
You talk
to your client, we'll be back.

290
00:15:31,056 --> 00:15:33,660
[door clanging and slamming]

291
00:15:33,693 --> 00:15:36,295
[footsteps receding]

292
00:15:36,328 --> 00:15:37,530
Pretty crazy, huh?

293
00:15:41,701 --> 00:15:45,605
[tense dramatic music playing]

294
00:15:47,172 --> 00:15:48,608
Who are you?

295
00:15:49,241 --> 00:15:51,444
If I told you,
you'd think I was crazy.

296
00:15:51,478 --> 00:15:53,345
- Good.
- But I'm not.

297
00:15:53,379 --> 00:15:55,414
What difference does it make?

298
00:15:55,448 --> 00:15:57,049
It makes all
the difference in the world.

299
00:15:57,082 --> 00:15:58,651
[Jason]
Whether you die or not?

300
00:15:58,685 --> 00:16:00,252
Whether I'm believable.

301
00:16:00,285 --> 00:16:03,188
That video
is pretty easy to believe.

302
00:16:03,690 --> 00:16:08,127
I know.
Look, I need you to trust me.

303
00:16:08,160 --> 00:16:10,362
Who are you?

304
00:16:10,996 --> 00:16:13,433
You don't need to know,
and don't worry about them.

305
00:16:13,466 --> 00:16:15,033
They'll chase
their tails trying to find out,

306
00:16:15,067 --> 00:16:16,536
but they don't
need to know either.

307
00:16:17,002 --> 00:16:18,605
They had me on video, right?

308
00:16:19,138 --> 00:16:21,073
Just move
forward with your defense.

309
00:16:22,007 --> 00:16:23,242
Send in the crazy coach.

310
00:16:28,448 --> 00:16:30,115
Okay.

311
00:16:30,149 --> 00:16:33,252
For now,
she'll be here tomorrow.

312
00:16:38,625 --> 00:16:40,660
What kind of crazy
do you think I should be?

313
00:16:41,661 --> 00:16:44,997
[keys clanging]

314
00:16:45,030 --> 00:16:46,466
You're the expert.

315
00:16:46,499 --> 00:16:53,038
[door buzzing,
clanging and slamming]

316
00:17:28,373 --> 00:17:33,212
[footsteps approaching]

317
00:17:35,648 --> 00:17:39,719
[door buzzing and clanging]

318
00:17:39,752 --> 00:17:42,254
Hi. I'm Charlotte Walker.

319
00:17:42,287 --> 00:17:44,724
[door clanging and slamming]

320
00:17:44,757 --> 00:17:46,358
Hello.

321
00:17:57,437 --> 00:17:58,771
Do you understand why I'm here?

322
00:18:01,073 --> 00:18:02,475
How good are you?

323
00:18:02,509 --> 00:18:04,042
Excuse me?

324
00:18:04,076 --> 00:18:05,712
Have you ever
gotten someone off

325
00:18:05,745 --> 00:18:08,113
on an insanity defense before?

326
00:18:08,715 --> 00:18:10,483
Let's get something straight.

327
00:18:10,717 --> 00:18:15,087
My first role and only role is
to evaluate your mental state.

328
00:18:15,120 --> 00:18:16,456
I'm not here to get you off.

329
00:18:17,356 --> 00:18:18,758
That sounds nice.

330
00:18:18,791 --> 00:18:21,126
But I want someone who can.

331
00:18:21,159 --> 00:18:22,428
Have you ever done it before?

332
00:18:23,395 --> 00:18:24,464
Yes.

333
00:18:24,797 --> 00:18:27,032
There you go. How many times?

334
00:18:28,300 --> 00:18:29,502
Twice.

335
00:18:29,702 --> 00:18:33,205
Less than 1% of insanity
defenses are successful.

336
00:18:34,507 --> 00:18:35,675
So, what are my chances?

337
00:18:36,308 --> 00:18:37,710
I don't know yet.

338
00:18:37,744 --> 00:18:39,278
What's it going to take?

339
00:18:41,413 --> 00:18:44,851
First, you need to understand
that an insanity defense

340
00:18:44,884 --> 00:18:48,186
is not a determination
of mental illness.

341
00:18:48,220 --> 00:18:49,622
It's a legal term.

342
00:18:50,188 --> 00:18:53,392
Determining mental illness
is a psychological process.

343
00:18:53,425 --> 00:18:56,663
The courts and juries
aren't capable of doing that.

344
00:18:56,696 --> 00:18:59,264
So, the courts established
a set of guidelines that need

345
00:18:59,298 --> 00:19:03,135
to be met in order to consider
someone legally insane.

346
00:19:03,168 --> 00:19:05,672
There are only
three guidelines, okay?

347
00:19:06,439 --> 00:19:10,375
The first one is this;
did the defendant understand

348
00:19:10,409 --> 00:19:12,645
that what he was
doing was illegal?

349
00:19:13,312 --> 00:19:15,748
Did you know the difference
between right and wrong?

350
00:19:18,216 --> 00:19:19,819
That's a question.

351
00:19:19,852 --> 00:19:22,555
Did you know that what
you were doing was wrong?

352
00:19:22,589 --> 00:19:24,824
No. It made perfect sense.

353
00:19:24,857 --> 00:19:26,191
I didn't do anything wrong.

354
00:19:26,759 --> 00:19:28,093
Nothing?

355
00:19:29,629 --> 00:19:34,567
Okay. Moving on.
Guideline number two.

356
00:19:34,601 --> 00:19:37,670
Did the defendant not
know what he was doing?

357
00:19:37,704 --> 00:19:40,607
Were you mentally
incapacitated in some way?

358
00:19:41,441 --> 00:19:43,810
I wasn't the one
who was mentally incapacitated.

359
00:19:44,242 --> 00:19:45,745
This isn't funny.

360
00:19:45,778 --> 00:19:49,314
I know. Nothing funny
about it. What's next?

361
00:19:50,415 --> 00:19:51,651
The third one.

362
00:19:52,552 --> 00:19:54,654
Was the defendant
compelled to commit the crime

363
00:19:54,687 --> 00:19:56,856
by an irresistible force?

364
00:19:57,356 --> 00:19:58,725
Do you hear voices?

365
00:20:00,292 --> 00:20:01,393
Screams.

366
00:20:01,861 --> 00:20:02,895
Screams.

367
00:20:03,830 --> 00:20:07,734
Screams
of the innocent, don't you?

368
00:20:09,802 --> 00:20:14,607
Okay. There's one
more thing to keep in mind.

369
00:20:14,641 --> 00:20:18,845
Mental illness isn't
an excuse in and of itself.

370
00:20:18,878 --> 00:20:23,549
If someone has intent, if
they intended to do something,

371
00:20:23,583 --> 00:20:26,519
then insanity can't
be used as a defense.

372
00:20:26,886 --> 00:20:28,320
So let's start there.

373
00:20:29,354 --> 00:20:31,524
Did you intend
to kill the president?

374
00:20:31,557 --> 00:20:34,927
No, I loved Lincoln.

375
00:20:34,961 --> 00:20:36,629
I could never kill him.

376
00:20:36,663 --> 00:20:39,197
He's been dead
over a 100 years.

377
00:20:41,333 --> 00:20:43,402
Then, how could I kill him?

378
00:20:45,605 --> 00:20:46,739
How am I doing?

379
00:20:47,573 --> 00:20:49,307
I don't like how this is going.

380
00:20:49,341 --> 00:20:51,276
Neither do I.

381
00:20:51,309 --> 00:20:53,378
Look, we can sit here
and talk about my relationship

382
00:20:53,412 --> 00:20:57,215
with my mother or if I was
ever abused or if I hear voices

383
00:20:57,249 --> 00:20:59,284
or whatever it says
to do in the playbook.

384
00:20:59,986 --> 00:21:04,222
Or we can talk about
what kinda crazy I need to be.

385
00:21:05,725 --> 00:21:07,259
I have some ideas.

386
00:21:07,292 --> 00:21:08,661
Of course, you do.

387
00:21:09,796 --> 00:21:14,667
[sad melancholic music]

388
00:21:14,701 --> 00:21:21,441
[car sirens ringing]

389
00:21:21,474 --> 00:21:26,813
[fires crackling]

390
00:21:26,846 --> 00:21:30,783
[people yelling and screaming]

391
00:21:30,817 --> 00:21:34,887
[car sirens ringing]

392
00:21:34,921 --> 00:21:41,326
[sad melancholic music]

393
00:21:41,359 --> 00:21:47,667
[glass shattering]

394
00:21:47,700 --> 00:21:54,807
♪

395
00:21:54,841 --> 00:22:00,580
♪

396
00:22:00,613 --> 00:22:03,315
Fuck you!

397
00:22:13,459 --> 00:22:17,563
[sirens fading]

398
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:25,671
[brooding pensive music]

399
00:22:32,478 --> 00:22:39,752
♪

400
00:22:43,589 --> 00:22:47,727
[door clacking]

401
00:22:53,466 --> 00:22:58,971
♪

402
00:23:12,384 --> 00:23:13,619
[Bailiff] All rise.

403
00:23:23,663 --> 00:23:27,399
Before we start, I want
to apologize to the defendant,

404
00:23:27,433 --> 00:23:29,902
the jury, and to both counsels

405
00:23:29,936 --> 00:23:32,038
for our delay
in starting this trial.

406
00:23:33,405 --> 00:23:37,009
This trial and the reason
we're having this trial has led

407
00:23:37,043 --> 00:23:39,679
to a highly charged atmosphere
throughout our country.

408
00:23:41,113 --> 00:23:45,685
This court has had
three bomb scares in two weeks.

409
00:23:47,153 --> 00:23:48,955
So for safety reasons,

410
00:23:48,988 --> 00:23:51,457
I decided to close
the courtroom to spectators.

411
00:23:52,658 --> 00:23:55,393
I admit it is unprecedented,

412
00:23:55,428 --> 00:23:57,663
but these
are unprecedented times.

413
00:23:58,497 --> 00:24:00,967
To protect the defendant's
rights and to ensure that

414
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:04,402
the public has access
to this most public of trials,

415
00:24:04,437 --> 00:24:06,505
I've invited a film
crew to film the proceedings

416
00:24:06,539 --> 00:24:09,942
and to provide a live stream
to all major news outlets.

417
00:24:09,976 --> 00:24:12,678
To monitor that the defendant's
rights are protected,

418
00:24:13,679 --> 00:24:15,114
I've asked representatives from

419
00:24:15,147 --> 00:24:16,515
the American Civil Liberties
Union,

420
00:24:16,549 --> 00:24:18,084
the Equal Justice Initiative,

421
00:24:18,117 --> 00:24:19,919
and the Civil Rights Division

422
00:24:19,952 --> 00:24:21,854
of the Department
of Justice to sit in.

423
00:24:22,588 --> 00:24:24,023
Thank you for being here.

424
00:24:24,056 --> 00:24:27,493
The jury has been
given its instructions.

425
00:24:27,526 --> 00:24:29,695
I see no need to delay
this trial another minute.

426
00:24:29,729 --> 00:24:31,464
Will the defendant
please stand?

427
00:24:34,533 --> 00:24:36,569
Mr. John Doe,
you've been charged with murder

428
00:24:36,602 --> 00:24:38,004
in the first degree
for the assassination

429
00:24:38,037 --> 00:24:39,772
of the President
of the United States.

430
00:24:39,805 --> 00:24:41,707
How do you plead?

431
00:24:41,741 --> 00:24:43,809
Your Honor, I object that my
defendant's identity has not

432
00:24:43,843 --> 00:24:45,745
been established,
and therefore, it is impossible

433
00:24:45,778 --> 00:24:47,713
to attribute a crime to him.

434
00:24:47,747 --> 00:24:50,082
The Court has assigned the name
'John Doe' to your client.

435
00:24:50,116 --> 00:24:52,051
The prosecution
has submitted sufficient

436
00:24:52,084 --> 00:24:54,086
evidence to warrant this trial.

437
00:24:54,120 --> 00:24:55,554
Until
law enforcement can establish

438
00:24:55,588 --> 00:24:57,089
your client's identity

439
00:24:57,123 --> 00:24:59,125
or your client wishes
to tell us his real name,

440
00:24:59,158 --> 00:25:01,594
then he will go by John Doe
for the purposes of this trial.

441
00:25:01,627 --> 00:25:02,762
Now, how do you plead?

442
00:25:03,829 --> 00:25:05,498
My client pleads Not Guilty
by reason of insanity,

443
00:25:05,531 --> 00:25:06,699
Your Honor.

444
00:25:06,732 --> 00:25:08,100
Thank you. You may be seated.

445
00:25:09,835 --> 00:25:11,103
Mr. Bradley.

446
00:25:11,137 --> 00:25:12,838
Thank you, Your Honor.

447
00:25:14,173 --> 00:25:17,610
Good morning.
Thank you all for being here.

448
00:25:17,643 --> 00:25:19,912
I think I speak for everyone
that none of us expected

449
00:25:19,946 --> 00:25:21,881
to be in this courtroom today.

450
00:25:21,914 --> 00:25:24,684
I can't imagine that when
you signed up for jury duty,

451
00:25:24,717 --> 00:25:27,753
you thought you'd wind up on
a jury for a trial like this,

452
00:25:28,654 --> 00:25:32,591
kind of trial that has never
been conducted in the history

453
00:25:32,625 --> 00:25:33,893
of this great country.

454
00:25:35,728 --> 00:25:40,700
We have sadly experienced the
assassination of our Presidents

455
00:25:40,733 --> 00:25:44,470
before, but
unlike this defendant,

456
00:25:44,737 --> 00:25:47,173
those assassins never
made it into a courtroom.

457
00:25:48,641 --> 00:25:50,576
But there's no
need to feel overwhelmed.

458
00:25:50,810 --> 00:25:54,113
In fact, it's my job to make
your job as easy as possible.

459
00:25:54,814 --> 00:25:57,283
I promise to do
that because there has never

460
00:25:57,316 --> 00:26:00,052
been a more open and shut
case against a defendant.

461
00:26:01,287 --> 00:26:03,522
We are going
to demonstrate

462
00:26:03,556 --> 00:26:06,625
beyond any reasonable doubt
that the man seated before you,

463
00:26:06,659 --> 00:26:09,895
charged here as John Doe,

464
00:26:09,929 --> 00:26:12,798
knowingly
and with willful intent

465
00:26:12,832 --> 00:26:16,102
killed the President
of the United States.

466
00:26:16,135 --> 00:26:19,205
Now, he may claim that
he does not know who he is.

467
00:26:20,639 --> 00:26:22,608
We will prove that he does

468
00:26:22,641 --> 00:26:25,978
and that his actions served
to not only hide his identity,

469
00:26:26,012 --> 00:26:28,814
but that he planned
his crime

470
00:26:28,848 --> 00:26:30,683
in advance.

471
00:26:31,183 --> 00:26:33,819
We will demonstrate that
he purchased the sniper rifle

472
00:26:33,853 --> 00:26:35,654
used in the attack,

473
00:26:35,688 --> 00:26:38,624
specifically for the purpose
of killing the President,

474
00:26:38,657 --> 00:26:41,794
that he traveled over 300 miles
to commit this crime,

475
00:26:43,162 --> 00:26:44,630
that he rented the apartment

476
00:26:44,663 --> 00:26:46,265
from where the attack
took place,

477
00:26:46,298 --> 00:26:49,835
specifically for the purpose
of committing this crime,

478
00:26:49,869 --> 00:26:52,138
and then he waited patiently

479
00:26:52,171 --> 00:26:54,740
for the opportunity
to stage his attack.

480
00:26:56,175 --> 00:26:58,811
We will prove that
the defendant

481
00:26:58,844 --> 00:27:01,247
is not only mentally competent

482
00:27:01,280 --> 00:27:03,883
but also diabolical

483
00:27:03,916 --> 00:27:06,852
in the planning of
and execution of

484
00:27:06,886 --> 00:27:09,922
the assassination of the
President of the United States.

485
00:27:11,690 --> 00:27:13,993
This was premeditated murder.

486
00:27:17,363 --> 00:27:19,665
Your Honor,
I'd like to call Stan Rosenberg

487
00:27:19,698 --> 00:27:21,333
as my first witness.

488
00:27:36,682 --> 00:27:37,883
Thank you.

489
00:27:37,917 --> 00:27:39,785
Please raise your right hand.

490
00:27:39,819 --> 00:27:42,054
Do you solemnly swear to tell
the truth, the whole truth,

491
00:27:42,088 --> 00:27:44,857
and nothing but the truth,
so help you, God?

492
00:27:44,890 --> 00:27:45,991
Yes.

493
00:27:47,893 --> 00:27:51,130
Mr. Rosenberg,
are you the owner/operator

494
00:27:51,163 --> 00:27:53,866
of the Alpine Terrace apartment
complex on Airport Drive?

495
00:27:53,899 --> 00:27:55,768
Yes, I am.

496
00:27:55,801 --> 00:27:57,303
And do you recognize
the defendant?

497
00:27:57,336 --> 00:27:58,771
Yes, I do.

498
00:27:58,804 --> 00:28:00,940
Was he a tenant
at your complex?

499
00:28:00,973 --> 00:28:02,341
Yes.

500
00:28:02,374 --> 00:28:04,143
- For how long?
- Two months.

501
00:28:04,176 --> 00:28:06,712
Did you personally
rent him the apartment?

502
00:28:06,745 --> 00:28:07,913
Yes, I did.

503
00:28:08,448 --> 00:28:10,983
Anything unusual
in that experience?

504
00:28:11,016 --> 00:28:12,685
Well, yes.

505
00:28:12,718 --> 00:28:14,253
What was that?

506
00:28:14,286 --> 00:28:16,856
Uh, he paid for the first
six months rent in cash.

507
00:28:16,889 --> 00:28:19,191
- In cash?
- Yes.

508
00:28:19,225 --> 00:28:22,261
Did he offer any explanation
as to why he wanted to do that?

509
00:28:22,294 --> 00:28:26,332
He told me he was a pilot,
that he flew corporate jets.

510
00:28:26,365 --> 00:28:29,735
He explained that he owned
a condominium downtown,

511
00:28:29,768 --> 00:28:32,037
he was married,

512
00:28:32,071 --> 00:28:34,173
and he was seeing
another woman on the side

513
00:28:34,206 --> 00:28:35,374
and needed a place
to meet her.

514
00:28:36,242 --> 00:28:37,409
What did you think of that?

515
00:28:38,445 --> 00:28:40,679
I appreciated the honesty.

516
00:28:40,713 --> 00:28:42,748
I've been in this business
for a long time,

517
00:28:42,781 --> 00:28:44,451
and I think I've heard it all.

